Let $J$ be the foot of the altitude from $A$ to $FB$, and let $K$ be the foot of the altitude from $A$ to $ED$. Since $\triangle AJF$ and $\triangle AKD$ are similar to $\triangle AEB$ and $\triangle AED$, respectively, we have $AJ=\frac{x}{2}$ and $AK=\frac{w}{2}$. Also, we have $JK=AF-AD=\frac{x-w}{2}$.

By Heron's formula, the area of $\triangle ABC$ is \[\sqrt{\frac{5+6+6}{2}\cdot\frac{5+6+6}{2}\cdot\frac{5+6-6}{2}\cdot\frac{5+6-6}{2}}=\sqrt{21\cdot16\cdot5\cdot5}=10\sqrt{105}.\]Since $\triangle ABC\sim\triangle JFA$ and $\triangle CDE\sim\triangle KDA$, we have \[\frac{[JFA]}{[ABC]}=\left(\frac{AJ}{AB}\right)^2=\frac{x^2}{100}\]and \[\frac{[KDA]}{[CDE]}=\left(\frac{AK}{CD}\right)^2=\frac{w^2}{36}.\]Since $[ABCDE]=[ABC]+[JFA]+[CDE]+[KDA]$, we have \[[ABCDE]=10\sqrt{105}+\frac{x^2}{100}\cdot10\sqrt{105}+\frac{w^2}{36}\cdot10\sqrt{105}.\]Substituting $x=5-y$ and $w=6-z$ and $r=7-x-y$, we get \[[ABCDE]=10\sqrt{105}+\frac{1}{100}(5-y)^2\cdot10\sqrt{105}+\frac{1}{36}(6-z)^2\cdot10\sqrt{105}.\]We want to find $[ABCDE]$. Note that $y+z=6$, so $y=6-z$. Substituting, we get \[[ABCDE]=10\sqrt{105}+\frac{1}{100}(5-6+z)^2\cdot10\sqrt{105}+\frac{1}{36}z^2\cdot10\sqrt{105}.\]Simplifying, we get \[[ABCDE]=10\sqrt{105}+\frac{1}{100}(z-1)^2\cdot10\sqrt{105}+\frac{5}{18}z^2\cdot10\sqrt{105}.\]To minimize this expression, we can take the derivative with respect to $z$ and set it equal to zero. Doing so gives \[0=\frac{d}{dz}[ABCDE]=\frac{1}{10}\sqrt{105}\cdot\left(\frac{1}{25}(z-1)-\frac{5}{18}z\right),\]which yields $z=\frac{18}{13}$. Substituting, we get $y=\frac{60}{13}$, $x=\frac{25}{13}$, and $r=\frac{33}{13}$.

