Then $IP = r + x,$ and $IB = IC = r.$  Applying the Law of Cosines to triangle $IBC,$ we get
\[r^2 = x^2 + r^2 - 2xr \cos 36^\circ,\]so
\[x = \frac{r}{2 \cos 36^\circ}.\]Hence,
\begin{align*}
\frac{[ABCDE]}{r^2} &= \tan 36^\circ + \tan 72^\circ \\
&= \tan 36^\circ + \cot 18^\circ \\
&= \frac{1}{\tan 54^\circ} + \frac{1}{\tan 18^\circ} \\
&= \frac{\sin 18^\circ}{\cos 18^\circ} + \frac{\cos 54^\circ}{\sin 54^\circ} \\
&= \frac{\sin 18^\circ}{\cos 18^\circ} + \frac{\sin 36^\circ}{\sin 54^\circ} \\
&= \frac{\sin 18^\circ}{\cos 18^\circ} + \frac{\sin 36^\circ}{\cos 36^\circ} \\
&= \frac{\sin 18^\circ \cos 36^\circ + \sin 36^\circ \cos 18^\circ}{\cos 18^\circ \cos 36^\circ} \\
&= \frac{\sin 54^\circ}{\cos 18^\circ \cos 36^\circ} \\
&= \frac{\sqrt{5} + 1}{8}.
\end{align*}Hence, $[ABCDE] = r^2 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{5} + 1}{8}.$

From the right triangle with hypotenuse $r$ and legs $x$ and $r - x,$ we can solve to get $r = \frac{30}{11}.$  Therefore,
\[r^2 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{5} + 1}{8} = \left( \frac{30}{11} \right)^2 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{5} + 1}{8} = \boxed{\frac{870 \sqrt{5} + 174}{121}}.\]

